segments.text: It was a dissertation by a fellow who had passed away, and his wife had sent it to us and asked us if we were interested in publishing it.
He had worked with the Corps of Engineers for many years, and it was on the subject of the development
of the mouth of the Mississippi River, the channelization of the Mississippi, and opening it up to heavy ship traffic.
And that was the dissertation, but it was absolutely, it was like reading a finished book.
It wasn't like a dissertation at all.
It didn't have the usual dissertation ease and the view of literature and
notes to every phrase, extremely well written, and I wanted to publish that.
And I was in the middle of negotiations with the man's wife and had told her that we would like to publish it.
And she wrote to me and said that the Corps of Engineers had gotten in touch with her and they wanted to publish it.
And so they did.
We missed out on that.

I think that would have been a really good book, and I think it would have led us into doing some stuff in history of technology and southern history, too, that we didn't get into until much more recently.
How does an editor attract manuscripts?
You attract manuscripts by publishing good books.

You find manuscripts by getting out there and talking to people, going to meetings, talking to people on the phone, just talking to people about their students and who's doing good work and about their colleagues and finding out who's got the manuscripts.
And then you make the contact with them and ask them if they haven't
written a manuscript yet, if they would consider writing one.
If they do have the manuscript, have they presented it to someone else?
And if not, could you see a proposal on it?
Give an example of one that you recall where that worked, where you did that.
Oh, that's the standard practice.
Practically every manuscript we get is now something that we
either have attracted through our previous publications or that we've gone out and contacted the author and asked that the author let us have a look at it.
I do that pretty often in the Eastern European series.
Stepan Nestrovich is the series editor, and he and I
often contact people whose work we've heard about and ask them if they will provide us with the prospectus.
I've just begun what we call the Centennial of Flight series.
And Roger Lanius, the chief historian at NASA, is the general editor of that series.
And he and I have actually
asked people to contribute books to the series.
And these are people who have done other writing in the history of aviation and aeronautics.
And so we don't even have a manuscript on that in that series yet, but we have 15 books lined up for it.
Everything from the man's, humanity's visions and imaginations about flight long before flight was possible,
through the light or the air period into the early years of aviation and right on up to the space age.
And I'm hoping that whoever takes my place here will continue that series and working with Roger.
And maybe there'll be 20 or 25 books in the series before it's really closed out in about 2004 or 5.
But we have about 15 titles lined up for it now.
Let's see, I'm now kind of going, heading downhill.
As you look back over these years, to which colleagues are you most grateful here on staff?
Oh, they're all a wonderful team.
I'm really grateful to Gayla Christensen, our marketing manager, because she's been my model for marketing practices and good marketing.
I've learned a tremendous amount from her over the years.
I was really grateful to Tom Rotell, because I learned a lot of business practices from him.

and learn from him that a university press can be run efficiently business-wise and still be a university press, still publish good scholarly work, but university press doesn't have to lose money on every book it publishes to retain its reputation.
And in fact, the books that sell well are often the books that give you a good reputation.
Just everybody on the staff, they've all been wonderful to work with.
Chris and I have been here 25 years, and all our friends are here.
We know some people in Lubbock, but it's going to be quite different.
Did you, by chance, know Bill Shearer?
Yes, I did.
Describe Bill Shearer for people who might not know you.
Well, Bill Shearer was our second sales rep, and he used to travel Texas visiting all the bookstores and selling the press's books in Texas.
Bill was an Aggie, and he was probably the most literate Aggie I ever met.
He read everything he could get his hands on.
He found time to read when, you know, I often wish that I had time to read books, just to sit down with a good book and enjoy it.
Well, Bill found that time.
He made that time.
That time was part of his life.
And I just have never lived books like Bill did.
And so he worked for us for,
I forget how long it was, five or six years.
And one day, I was riding with him on a trip, and I said, where do you want to go?
What do you plan to do in this business?
And he said, I'm going to start my own publishing house.
And sure enough, a few days later, he came in dressed in a suit.
You didn't see Bill in a suit very often.
But I said, why are you all dressed up?
And he says, I'm going to the bank.
I'm going to talk to them about financing me my publishing business.
And he got the loan.
He also got support from, oh, jeez, my memory is going.
fellow in a printer in Austin who had done a lot of work for the press, had done a lot of our printing, especially our big color books.
Hart, Bill Hart was the name.
And Bill Hart had acquired the rights to Shoal Creek Publishing, which was a little fine, high-quality publishing house at Texana.
And so Bill Hart told Bill Shearer that he would contribute to Bill's business and become a partner if Bill would take these Shoal Creek books and distribute them and sell them.
So Bill did that, and then he started his own publication program and moved to Fredericksburg after a couple of years here.
And Shearer Publishing was one of the
one of the top Texas literature Texana publishers in the state for several years for the good work that Bill had done.
He was in an old beer hall and dance hall in Fredericksburg.
I guess their offices are still there.
I haven't been over there in some time.
I think so.
But his wife Kathy now runs the business.
Bill passed away a few years back, and it was a tremendous loss.
He was a great publisher and he was just an all-around great guy.
Let's see, other people that, are there any non-A&M employees, perhaps former students, that you think have been important to the press?
Oh yeah, Joe and Betty Moore, John Lindsay, the more recently,
John and C.C.
Keck down in Laredo.
K-E-C-K.
Yes.
John Keck and we have a series name for them, and I can't even think of the name now.
I'm getting close to retirement, I guess.
What is the common factor in those folks?
What causes them to be?
Well, they love books.
They love publishing.
I know John Lindsay's case, he was just so excited that his university could have its own publishing operation.
I was going to say, is the fact that there's some ruinousness, does that help?
Oh, yeah.
Yeah.
I mean, it's very true that Aggies support their university better than alumni anywhere else in the world.
And they are the Moores and the Lindseys and the Kecks and the other people whose name I can't recall.
I'm embarrassed to say.
have all been real supportive.
And then a lot of other people, too, just people like John Adams.
We're publishing his third book.
He's written The History of the Corps of Cadets, and we'll be publishing that.
Adams has done a lot of good work with the press, and he's never asked for anything special, no special consideration.
wants Texas A&M University Press to publish these things.
What advice as you, now I'm placing you, you're the consultant, what advice would you give to the Texas A&M Press now?
Keep up what it's been doing for the last six years.
What does that mean?
Keep publishing the kinds of books that it's been publishing and keep its eye on the bottom line the way it has been doing.
I think the press could be a little more adventurous in some areas that it has funding in.
Such as?
Well, like in the revolving funds, use of those.
But I think overall the balance is real good right now between the funded books and the unfunded ones, between the trade books and the scholarly books.
And I think it's a good opportunity now.
If the press sticks to its knitting and does what it has experience of doing, that we can see some growth from it.
in coming years and it can move on up into the from 20th to 25th on up into the teens and maybe even higher in the ranking.
I think Charles has plans to move right on up with the university and make the press expand and grow.
right along with the university.
Are there any new subject areas that would be worthy for A&M to consider and impress?
Well, we're trying to get a series in agriculture started.
We have three books on that.
Is that a good?
That's starting, yeah.
That's a good venture.
That's a good prospect.
I think the only other one that should be considered right now
and I think Charles is considering it, but I would recommend that he be very careful about it, is veterinary medicine.
Because there's a lot of commercial competition there.
But the right kinds of books, I think, this press could do in vet medicine or associated topics.
But other than that, I think the press ought to hold on developing any new fields for a while.
And the number of titles
projected now per year?
It's about 50 to 55, but it's going on up from there.
Do you think that's a worthy goal?
Yeah, if the administration is willing to support the university and support the press and help with the cost of that growth, we're going to
The press is going to need a new warehouse if it expands its list much more.
It's going to need new staff and production and every other department.
And more space.
And more space for the offices, yeah.
We have room in the field out back for more warehouse, but I'm not sure how this building could be expanded for offices.
We might have to move part of our
operation to another building.
Other presses do that.
It's OK, but it's just not the same.
Of what are you, as you look back, of what are you most proud of your 25 years here?
Well, I'm most proud, I think, of keeping a lot of the traditions of the press, the things that we published in the past, keeping them alive, keeping our Texas history

publishing live and on track, and getting our military history series started and going strong, and getting the Eastern European series started, getting this new Centennial of Flight series started, and being here and overseeing the other new areas that we've gotten into, presidential studies, although that, you know, with Mary Lynn's
working directly with the Bush School people.
That was such a natural topic for us.
It could hardly have been avoided.
But those things are the kinds of things I think I'm proudest of having been a part of here.
All right.
Just about next to the last question.
Let's make believe someone walked up to you and handed you a million-dollar check
with one stipulation.
You must pass it on to Texas A&M, but you can decide.
I couldn't ask them if I could take it with me today.
No, no.
You could decide what A&M would do with it.
If you had a million dollars to give Texas A&M, what would you ask them to use it for?
Well, of course I'd give it to the press.
To do what?
To endow publication.
In what?
In whatever the press wanted to publish.
You mean you wouldn't specify?
I wouldn't specify.
I would rely on the editors and the director to make that decision.
As you drive away to a school whose colors are red and black, how easy will it be for the maroonness in your system to fade away?
Well, as I said, 25 years here, we put down some pretty deep roots.
All our friends are here.
We have acquaintances.
and a few friends in Lubbock, but we're going to be leaving a lot here.
And so the strings are going to be attached.
They're going to be long strings, 428-mile long strings, but they'll still be attached.
And I'm going to be keeping in touch with people here, and they with me, I know.
So I'll have to root for them.
Red Raiders at the football games, but there'll always be a little bit of maroon in there.
I may have to cover it up with red and black, but it'll be there.
